Slide 1 — Context: “Why Coding Agents Now”

Goal: Align everyone on why this matters, what value it brings, and why governance is needed.

Say (20–30 sec):

“Coding agents are quickly becoming the default developer workflow — they help engineers read, write, refactor, and review faster.”

“They remove repetitive SDLC work: scaffolding/boilerplate, tests, docs, and faster code understanding.”

“But if we don’t manage them, we get new problems: token-cost spikes, inconsistent patterns, and security/compliance risk.”

“So in Coforge AI LAB, we’re building a governed framework to get safe productivity gains — work in progress.”

(Point to the SDLC graphic) “This is where agents help across the SDLC — and you can click to zoom.”

One-liner to close the slide:
“Agents are powerful — the question is how to make them enterprise-safe and repeatable.”

Slide 2 — “The Problem with Generic AI Coding Agents”

Goal: Create the “why not just use tools as-is?” tension.

Say (20–30 sec):

“Off-the-shelf agents are great for individuals, but enterprise teams hit predictable limits.”

“They often pull too much context (whole repos) → higher token costs.”

“They don’t naturally know our org standards → inconsistent code and rework.”

“Design-to-code stays manual → UI delivery stays slow.”

“And teams repeat prompts over and over → wasted effort.”

One-liner to close the slide:
“We’re not replacing agents — we’re wrapping them with intelligence, standards, and automation.”

(If needed, name-check ecosystem quickly: “Whether it’s Microsoft Copilot, OpenAI Codex, or Anthropic Claude Code — the enterprise gap is the same.” Use once and move on.)
Mentioned orgs: Microsoft, OpenAI, Anthropic.

Slide 3 — “Three-Layer Intelligence Architecture”

Goal: Explain the solution simply: governance + design automation + smart context orchestration.

Say (30–45 sec):

“Our approach has three layers — each solves a specific enterprise pain.”

“Governance & Standards: templates inject our coding standards and security rules into every interaction, so outputs are consistent.”

“Design-to-Code Intelligence: a Figma → code pipeline to speed UI handoff and reduce manual translation.”

“MCP Tool Orchestration: connect the agent to tools like GitHub and project systems so it fetches only relevant context — not the whole repo.”

“Net: faster delivery with governance. And we’re being careful: this is work in progress, not inflated ROI claims.”

One-liner to close the slide:
“This is ‘enterprise AI coding’ — predictable, governed, and scalable.”

10-second wrap (after slide 3)

“If you remember one thing: agents alone boost individuals; our framework boosts teams safely at enterprise scale.”

If you want, I can also give you a 90-second version (ultra-short) and a 3-minute version (with 1–2 examples) so you can adapt to different audiences.

